		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Spread betting</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Spread betting</b> is any of various types of <a href="/wiki/Wagering" title="Wagering" class="mw-redirect">wagering</a> on the <a href="/wiki/Outcomes" title="Outcomes" class="mw-redirect">outcome</a> of an event, where the pay-off is based on the <a href="/wiki/Accuracy" title="Accuracy" class="mw-redirect">accuracy</a> of the wager, rather than a simple "win or lose" outcome, which is known as <a href="/wiki/Fixed-odds_betting" title="Fixed-odds betting">fixed-odds</a> or money-line betting. A <i>spread</i> is a range of outcomes, and the bet is whether the outcome will be above or below the spread. Spread betting has been a major growth market in the <a href="/wiki/UK" title="UK" class="mw-redirect">UK</a> in recent years, with the number of gamblers heading towards one million.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Spread betting carries a high level of risk, with potential losses or gains far in excess of the original money wagered.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> In the UK, spread betting is regulated by the <a href="/wiki/Financial_Services_Authority" title="Financial Services Authority">Financial Services Authority</a> rather than the Gambling Commission.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
